This paper deals with wireless body area networks (BANs) and their coexistence, which falls under the category of networked systems and communication in computer science. Therefore, cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also proposes a non-cooperative game for transmit power control, which falls under the category of game theory, making cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also discusses the use of channel models and signal-to-interference-and-noise ratio (SINR), which are related to information theory, making cs.IT (Information Theory) another likely sub-category. The paper also deals with reliability and interference management, which are related to multimedia systems and human-computer interaction, making cs.MM (Multimedia) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a socially optimal solution, which falls under the category of social and information networks, making cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) a possible sub-category as well.
